The functions in ggplot2 package can be looked up in the RDocumentation of ggplot2.

Basic Plots

Different elemnts/parameters of ggplot2 are added by using the plus sign. The plus sign has to be placed at the end of the line! Never at the start.

The plot always start with calling ggplot(). Sometimes the aesthetic mapping can be taken togather with the x and y or separately.

ggplot(data = mpg) + geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy))

ggplot(data = mpg, aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + geom_point()

You can also do

ggplot(data = NULL, aes(x = mpg$displ, y = mpg$hwy)) + geom_point()

It does not make sense to do a line plot in this case…(Maybe I should try and see what would happen) but you can ggplot(data,mapping)+ geom_line() + geom_point to overlay points and lines.

The functions have geom prefix in them, and “geom” means a geometrical object (that is used for making the plot).

ggplot(data = mpg, aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + geom_point()+geom_line()

So geom_line would literally connect the dots. You we want to overaly a linear fit, then we will need to do some extra stuff.

One of the tutorials have provided a template. This means that you can overlay different plots from the same data.

ggplot(data = <DATA>) + <GEOM_FUNCTION>(mapping = aes(<MAPPINGS>))

ggplot(data = mpg, aes(x = class, y = drv)) + geom_point()

The plot can be colorcoded by some discrete var.

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, size = class, color = class))
## Warning: Using size for a discrete variable is not advised.

Similarly, shape() and alpha() can be definied.alpha() controls the transparency of the points.

The shape, color, and size can be specified as well (There are plenty of resources online, so probably the codes can be looked up whenever needed). But remember to move color = "color" out of the bracket because the mapping of the color no longer involves specific aspect of the data.

Another variable is facet()

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + 
  facet_wrap(~ year, nrow = 1)

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + 
  facet_grid(drv ~ cyl)

Or

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + 
  facet_grid(.~cyl)

Besides geom_pointand geom_line, there are also geom_smooth, geom_boxplot, geom_bar, and probably more (I saw geom_violin and geom_rug: https://www.rdocumentation.org/packages/ggplot2/versions/3.3.6). The tutorial says there are more than 40 geoms. There is a gallery of ggplot2 extensions that redirects to corresponding github pages: https://exts.ggplot2.tidyverse.org/gallery/

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_smooth(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, linetype = drv))
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

The show.legend function defines whether the legend is shown. group variable works similar to color and shape.

ggplot(data = mpg) +
  geom_smooth(
    mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, color = drv),
    show.legend = FALSE
  )
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

ggplot(data = mpg) +
  geom_smooth(
    mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, group = drv),
  )
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

The mappings can be global or local. If there called inside the ggplot function, then they are global. If they are called inside the geom then they are local.

For example, in the following code, the color-coding based on class is geom_point specific:

ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(color = class)) + 
  geom_smooth()
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

Similarly, the data can be defined locally. filter is called to limit the data to class “subcompact” of mpg.

ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(color = class)) + 
  geom_smooth(data = filter(mpg, class == "subcompact"), se = FALSE)
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

*se controls whether the shaded area is present.

ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, color = drv)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  geom_smooth(se = TRUE)
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

There is a helpful exercise question on the tutorial that may identify some helpful geom functions.

“What geom would you use to draw a line chart? A boxplot? A histogram? An area chart?”

So on the documentation page, there are several other functions that I personally found interesting.

geom_abline can be used for adding reference lines, there is also a geom_contour for visualizing 2D contours of a 3D surface (The function requires x, y, z coordinates, so mpg dataset probably don’t work well with this unless we define the x, y, z specifically). But still the plot does not work well. (probably it is not meaningful to make the plot in the first place.)

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
   geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = cty,color = class)) + 
   geom_contour(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = cty, z = hwy))

Other geom functions for drawing lines include geom_crossbar (this is probably a bit special), geom_qq_line, geom_segment, and geom_path.

For boxplot, there is geom_boxplot. There is geom_function for plotting the continuous curve of a function (maybe good for overlaying linear fit?)

lmfit = lm(hwy ~ displ, data = mpg)

The function can be defined using the function(), or you can use this pretty cool syntax ~f(.x), where .x will sub in the x defined in the context (whatever x you previously identified in the function calling).

ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(color = class)) + 
  geom_function(fun = ~-3.5306*.x + 35.6977, color = "red", size = 2)

#Remember not to place the color and size inside the mapping option

For histogram , there is geom_freqpoly. Finally, geom_ribbon can be used for making area plots.

Statistical transformations

Some plots will calculate new values from the dataset, which is a process called “statistical transformation” (stat)! For example, geom_bar will calculate the count values.

If the count values are to be calculated by the plot, defining the x for the aes mapping is enough. If freq is already provided, then:

demo <- tribble(
  ~cut,         ~freq,
  "Fair",       1610,
  "Good",       4906,
  "Very Good",  12082,
  "Premium",    13791,
  "Ideal",      21551
)

ggplot(data = demo) +
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = cut, y = freq), stat = "identity")

Interestingly, stat_summary can be used for plotting.

data("diamonds")
ggplot(data = diamonds) + 
  stat_summary(
    mapping = aes(x = cut, y = depth),
    fun.min = min,
    fun.max = max,
    fun = median
  )

For stat, you can choose to show the proportion, instead of the default count data. If the group parameter is not provided, the bars will have the same height and have proportion of 1.0.

ggplot(data = diamonds) + 
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = cut, y = stat(prop), group = 1))#The group parameter is needed

stat_summary uses bar charts as the default geom.

geom_col and geom_bar are two types of bar plots. geom_col specifically takes variables from the data itself as the y values instead of values derived from stat.

ggplot(data = diamonds,mapping = aes(x = cut, y= depth, group=1)) + 
  geom_col()#The group parameter is needed

“Most geoms and stats come in pairs that are almost always used in concert.”

Position adjustment

color and fill can also be defined similar to shape and alpha in previous examples.

ggplot(data = diamonds) + 
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = cut, colour = cut))

ggplot(data = diamonds) + 
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = cut, fill = cut))

Moreover, color can be gradiented if color is defined by a third variable.

ggplot(data = diamonds) + 
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = cut, fill = clarity))

There are three options for position adjustment: “identity”, “dodge”, “fill”. Identity will directly overlay the boxes, which is not helpful for visualization. Then we can use “fill”

ggplot(data = diamonds) + 
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = cut, fill = clarity), position = "fill")

ggplot(data = diamonds) + 
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = cut, fill = clarity), position = "dodge")

For scatter plots, there is another position option: “jitter”. This option will help correct for overplotting.

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy), position = "jitter")

There is also “stack”. The default for bar plot is probably stack.

ggplot(data = diamonds) + 
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = cut, fill = clarity), position = "identity")
